explanation:
Throwing from a destructor during stack unwinding triggers `std::terminate`, because a second active exception cannot safely propagate at the same time.
Example:
struct X {
  ~X() noexcept(false) { throw std::runtime_error("boom"); }
};
try {
  X x;
  throw std::runtime_error("outer");
} catch (...) {
  // terminate occurs before this handler can finish
}

A `noexcept` function promises no exception escapes. If one does, the runtime immediately calls `std::terminate`.
Example:
void work() noexcept {
  throw std::logic_error("unexpected");
}
// work() terminates the program if exception escapes

